{"/service/ndnp/gu/batch_gu_bootes_ver01/data/sn89053204/00393344246/1913110901/0928.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE FOUR\n\u25a0HE TIMES RECORDER.\nB (Incorporated.)\nEs X?ery Morning Except Monday.\n\u25a0>aUy Per Annum $5.00\nPer Annum 1,00\nI THE AMERICUS RECORDER\nB Established 1870.\nI THE AMEKICIJS TIMES\nI Established April, 1891.\n\u2022thhES-RECORDER CO, Publishers,\ni G. R. ELLIS, President\nI&U1MBY MELTON Editor\nE L W. FURLOW City Editor\nBusiness Manager:\nW L DUPREE.\njjgrr-\nOFFICE TELEPHONE NO. 99\nAH subscription* payable In ad\nfKsca,\nAdvertising rate* promptly furnish\nI sd upon application.\nMemorial Resolutions, Resolutions\n\u00a7J Respect Obituary Notices, etc.,\nether than those which the paper may\nfaem proper to publish as news mat\nter, will be charged for at the rate of\ncents per line.\nAll advertising copy requiring two\ntoiamns of space or leu should be In\nthe business office not later than noon\nof day prior to date of Issn* In order\nis insure Its prompt Insertion. All\n\u00bbpy for space of more than two col\nmnns should be submitted not later\nthan 6 o\u2019clock of the day, two days\nprior to date of Ibsus.\nOFFICIAL ORGAN!\nCity of Amerlcus.\nPunster County.\nWebster County.\nKa'lroad Commission of Georgia For\nThird Congressional District\nD. 8. Court Southern District of\nGeorgia.\nAmerlcus, November 1913\nA busy man is a happy man.\nHuerta is getting very near the can\ndie flame.\nRemember enristmas is also meant\n\u25a0Jor the clerks so shop early.\nx. i\nFlowers on your coffin don\u2019t make\nup for brickbats thrown during your\nlife time.\nA true test of a gentleman is\nwhether or not he considers every wo\nman a lady.\nThe bill collector has retired to\nhis hole. Some of our bills are paid\nand we are \u2014oh well, maybe pay day\nwill come again.\nDON\u2019T TAKE CHANCfcS WITH THE\nBABY\nNot long ago 1 saw a baby suffering\nunder the ministrations of a little ten\nyear-old girl. The baby was allowed\nto be carried home by the little girl to\nb, end the afternoon and 1 happened\nto be there when she arrived. Two\nhours that poor baby was pulled and\nhauled and played with and fed until\nif Shrieked in protest, it was dressed\nand undressed and had its face wash\ned and its hair brushed, it. was allow\ned to roll off the bed and get hurt.\nTho only 11 months old it was ted\nthree times during the afternoon, once j\nwith bread and twice with chicken and\n(dumplings. It. was scratched badly\nby a pin in the little girl\u2019s dress and\nfinally it was put on the floor where\nit got hold of a piece of tobacco and\nput it in his mouth.\nThis is perhaps an extreme casv,\nl but it is not the first time by a good\nmany that I have seen a baby car\nried to a neighbor\u2019s house and sharae\ntelly neglected. From a sentimental\nctindpoint I know one ought not to be\nseifish with the baby. The neighbors\nI and their children love it and like io\nire-p it with them.\u2019 But from a prac-\nI flea? standpoint and thinking of what\nI i\u00ab\u2019 good for the baby it had better he\nl kest at home. Sometimes I know a\nl young mother is harassed and wor\nried and tired and she feels that it\nwould be a relief to have the baby ofl\nher bands for a little while, but un\n?\u00ab\u2022>s she is perfectly sure the baby is\nI gofng to be weli taken care of. she\nI trtd better keep it at home. Especial-\nI ly would I not let my baby be carri ><i\nIto a home where there was a bury\nI T\u2019other and young children. The ehil-\nI d-'-'n will just simply love the baby to\ndeath and their mother is too busy to\n1 Jntrrfere\u2014Mrs. Lilian Brooks Gatlin,\nThe Progressive Farmer.\nWHERE BATTLES ARE FOUGHT AND WON j:\nA white-haired veteran of the civ\u2019l\nwar reads of the Mexican situati i i\nand says to his young grandsons,\n\u201cBoys, I know what war is; 1 hope\nyou will never have to go to war.\u201d\nThe old man is right. War, wito\nshot and shell is ail that Sherman said\nof it; but a man does not have to\nshoulder a musket and be mustered\ninto service, that means the shedding\nor blocd and the breaking of bones, in\norder to engage in as real battles as\nthe world has ever known.\n1 Notwithstanding the general pros\nperity of Georgia today\u2019, there are\nmany good men and women, here and\nthere all over the state, who are strug\ngling to provide for the material needs\nof their children. The battle for meat\nand bread and clothing, the battle to\npay debts or to keep out of debt, the\nbattle to provide educational and soc\nial opportunities for the young peop e\nX\n\u2014these battles are as real as anv\nthat were ever fought with bayonets\nor sabres.\nThe battle to shield the boys and\ngirls from the attractive evils of mod\nern life, the battle to keep ones body\nA######/\nTHE ANIMAL VERSES THE HUMAN\nBEING\nInquiry- was recently made of the\nMinnesota State Board of Health as to\na certain family affected with tuber\nculosis. The family was large and the\nhouse small, so that such care could\nnot be given to the afflicted as to pre\nvent the infection of others. The fath\ner had means and could afford to carj\nproperly for those diseased, if coin\npell d to do so. A state board inspec\ntor was sent to investigate and this is\nwhat he found. A well-to-do farme-,\nwith a farm of 320 acres worth SIOO\nan acre or more; a breeder of horses,\nhaving at the time of inspection seven\nimported Percheron horses and a herd,\nof about twenty-five horses in all; n\nbreeder of registered hogs, his hogs\nbeing among the first in the state to\nbe given the serum protective against\nhog cholera. This farmer has lived ir\ncounty for about thirty years\nSixteen years ago his first wife died of\ntuberculosis, leaving three children.\nHe married again. His second wife\nhas had thirteen children. The family\nnow consists of father, mother and\nfourteen children. A daughter of the\nsecond wife, aged 15, died last August\nof tuberculosis. A son of the first\nwife, aged 17, has been ill with tuber\nculosis for at least two years. No pre\ncautions have been taken to prevent\nhis infecting others. The mother, wkh\none newly-born child and another too\nyoung to walk, is responsible for the\ncare of this family of fourteen living\nchildren. There is no medical care be\ning given the son afflicted with tube\nculosis. Apparently this farmer can\nappreciate the breeding of horses and\nthe protection of hogs from hog chol\nera. But he cannot appreciate the\ndanger of tuberculosis or the ne\u00b0d of\nprotecting not only the members of\nhis own family, but others also,, from\nthis disease. The annual loss, in the\nstate of Minnesota, caused by the death\njof wage-earners from tuberculosis is\nabout $12,000,000. The number of\ndeaths annually from tuberculosis a\nMinnesota is about 2.250. The esti\nmated number of cases of tuberculosis\nin Minnesota at the present time is 10.-\n000,or more. Is this human disease\nworthy of the same efforts for its ex\ntermination as are hog cholera or\nglanders?\nIt\u2019s better to ride a mule that s\nyours than to joy ride in a mortgaged\nautomobile.\nSo far troubles in Mexico haven't\nworried the Southern farmer. With\nlarge crops and cotton bringing a\ngood price they have weightier sub\njects to think of.\nA Prosperity Song.\nAll indications point to a return of\nprosperity this fall. One colored\ni brother sings:\nMister Prosperity\nPse glad you\u2019re coiiWfi' iflgh,\nI I'll des shout halelulah\nTo de angels in de sky.\nWhen de darkies am a-pickin\u2019\nOn good fried chicken\nWe\u2019ll rise an' sing Ole Hundred\n\u2014\u2019Twell de heavens\u2019 shake on high.\nTHE AMERICUS DAILY TIMES-RECORDER.\nwell when exposure and long hours\nare a necessity, the battle to keep j j\nones temper sweet and ones heart pure j\namid the worries and vexations of the\neveryday grind \u2014these battles are j\nsuch as were fought at Manassas or j\n\nGettysburg'. j;\nMost people who ever amount to any t\nthing, or who accomplish anything u\nworth while may be said, literally, to\nhave to fight their way. The soldier\nof courage, in the battle of life, press-ju\nes forward to victory. The enemies:\nhunger, debt, ignorance, disease, and jj,\nsin must be crowded to the wall and\novercome. Humanity cannot afford toil;\nsurrender to its enemies, large or I;;\nsmall. If there are some of us who j;\nhave to fight all our lives, let us face'll\nthe enemy and die by our guns. Al;\nbrave soldier is proud of a wound i.i\nhis breast..\n\u201cTramp, tramp, tramp, the boys arc 'I\nmarching,\u201d and the enemies of human- l|\nity are stampeding to cover. What-\never may be the peculiar battle we\nhave to fight, may it be said of us, 11\nwhen they gather up our bones, \u201cHe l|\nfought a good fight.\u201d j;\nUnion Central Lite Ins. Co\nThe company with\nthe best interest s\nearnings. The low-\nest death rate, lar\ngest dividends and\nlowest net cash to\npolicy holders.\nLee M. Hansford, Genei?! Agent\nRoom 18, Planters Bank Bldg.\nIke Great Annual Dividend Payer.\u2019\nt\n11\nSeaboard Air line\nTbc Progressive Railway ol the South\n\nLeave Americus for Cordele, Ro\nchelle, Abbeville, Helena, Lyons, Col-\nMno, Savannah, Columbia, Richmond,\nPortsmouth and points East and Sou A.\n12.31 p. m.\n1:25 a. m\nLeave Americus for Cordele, Abbo\nrllle, Helena and Intermediate point*\n5:20 p.m\nLeave Americus for Richland, Atlan\nta, Birmingham, Hurtsboro, Mont\nomery and points West and Northwest\n1:50 a. m.\n8:13 p. m.\n\nLeave Americus for Richland, Co\nlumbus, Dawson, Albany and interme-\nSiate points\n10:05 a. m.\nFor further Information apply to B\nf*. Everett, Local Ageut, Amerlcu*\nGa.; C. W. Small, Div. Pas* Agt\nSavannah, Ga.: C. B. Ryan. G. P. A\nPortsmouth. Vs\nKEEP THE KIDNEYS WELL\nHeullli is Worth Saving and Some\nAmericus People Know How to\nSave It.\nMany Americus people take their\nlives in their hands by neglecting the\nkidneys when they know these organs i\nneed help. Weak kidneys are respon\